The first coronavirus (COVID 19) case in Grenada was confirmed on 22 March. Government has introduced measures to limit the spread of the virus. These include a ban on gatherings, and enforcement of social distancing of 6 feet.
The Ministry of Health Grenada is asking the public to call the COVID-19 enquiries information line on 538 4787 or 458 4787 if they have any symptoms such as cough fever or difficulty breathing, and visit the Governmentâ€™s webpage for the latest information on the virus.
The Government of Grenada announced that, effective from 19 March, until further notice, any non-Grenadian nationals and non-residents arriving in Grenada with a travel history in the UK and the rest of Europe within the last 14 days will not be permitted entry into Grenada. From the 22 March this also applies to travellers with a recent travel history to the US. This follows similar restrictions for persons with a travel history in mainland China, Italy, Iran, South Korea and Germany, France and Spain, within the last 14 days. Effective from 16 March, disembarkation from cruise vessels will also not be permitted in Grenada. Effective 22 March, non-Grenadian passengers and crew on yachts will not be permitted to disembark in Grenada, Carriacou, and Petite Martinique. Any failure to comply will result in a fine or detention.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
